</span> <span class="mjx-sup" style="font-size: 83.3%; vertical-align: 0.347em; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0.06em;"><span class="mjx-mn" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">2</span></span></span></span></span><span style="border-bottom: 1.3px solid; top: -0.296em; width: 0.809em;" class="mjx-line"></span></span><span style="height: 1.702em; vertical-align: -0.601em;" class="mjx-vsize"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="border-bottom: 1.3px solid; top: -0.296em; width: 3.971em;" class="mjx-line"></span></span><span style="height: 3.095em; vertical-align: -1.95em;" class="mjx-vsize"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fn4w4wnw6odfq"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnref4w4wnw6odfq">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> One prior guess I have seen is Eliezer Yudkowsky suggested that human level AGI could be done on a 286 (if the programmer is a superintelligent AGI) or a &quot;home computer from 1995&quot; (maybe a 90 Mhz Pentium, if the programmer is a human) <a href="https://intelligence.org/2022/03/01/ngo-and-yudkowsky-on-scientific-reasoning-and-pivotal-acts/">https://intelligence.org/2022/03/01/ngo-and-yudkowsky-on-scientific-reasoning-and-pivotal-acts/</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnai4pdbcrhfo"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefai4pdbcrhfo">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> <a href="https://www.mit.edu/~ecprice/wordlist.10000">https://www.mit.edu/~ecprice/wordlist.10000</a> for example is 75880 bytes. As well word vectors usually have vector length of at least 100, so those would not even fit a 1000 basic words with the vectors. See for example GloVe: &quot;Global Vectors for Word Representation&#39;&#39; <a href="https://aclanthology.org/